My first plot

## ggplot(data, aes(what's x, what's y) + what kind of plot)
s <- ggplot(g, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) +
    geom_point()
s

My second plot

a simple geom_point with aes()

s2 <-  s + aes(size = pop_m)
s2

s3 <-  s2 + aes(color = continent)
s3

nice piped!

s <- ggplot(g, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) +
    geom_point() + 
    aes(size = pop_m) + 
    aes(color = continent) +
    ggtitle('Health and Wealth of Nations for 2007') +
    xlab('GDP per capita (USD/year)') + 
    ylab('Life expectency (years)') +
    scale_colour_discrete('Continent') + 
    scale_size_continuous('Population (M)')
s

Make a boxplot

This is my boxplot of continent and life expectency. Using g, which is a subset of 2007

    b <- ggplot(g, aes(x = continent, y = lifeExp)) +
    geom_boxplot() + 
    aes(fill = continent) + 
    theme(legend.position = 'none')
    b

GoogleVis interactive figure

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(googleVis))
## Warning: package 'googleVis' was built under R version 3.2.5
## Creating a generic function for 'toJSON' from package 'jsonlite' in package 'googleVis'
 # install.packages('googleVis')

op <- options(gvis.plot.tag='chart')

m = gvisMotionChart(
  gapminder %>%
    mutate(
      pop_m = pop / 1e6,
      log_gdpPercap = log(gdpPercap)), 
  idvar='country', 
  timevar='year', 
  xvar='log_gdpPercap', 
  yvar='lifeExp', 
  colorvar='continent',
  sizevar='pop_m')
plot(m)
